defaultWritten evidence submitted by defaultJon defaultGibbinsdefault and Hannah Chalmersdefault (CCS38)default&#xa0;
defaultSummarydefaultThe authors have worked on CCS issues for approximately 10 years, with particular attention to possible routes and drivers for CCS deployment.  This evidence mainly addresses questions related to the potential benefits to the UK economy
default 
defaultof successfully developing CCS, how the successful development of CCS 
defaultmight 
defaultimprove international efforts to mitigate climate change, the role that UK CCS
default in particular 
defaultcould play in this and some of the possible consequences for failure.  The strong two-way linkage between CCS deployment and effective global action on climate change mitigation are emphasised
default, also the likelihood of lower fossil fuel prices in a carbon-constrained future world.
default  Current UK CCS developments are placed, as far as possible, in the wider context of international efforts to initiate
default the first tranche of
default large-scale integrated CCS projects.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default1.  The only satisfactory result for the 
defaultUK
default's climate policy can be that the currently rising concentrations of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere are stabilised at levels that do not cause dangerous climate change.  Hence, what we do in the UK is intimately linked with getting the ‘right’ outcome internationally since getting this result is
default 
defaultn
defaulto
defaultt something we can do by ourselves.
default2.  Expenditure to support a timely carbon capture and storage (CCS) deployment programme is more likely to contribute to this result than the equivalent amount of expenditure applied to the deployment of existing low-carbon power generation technologies such as wind or nuclear
default, given the level of activity already underway in these other sectors
default.  
defaultIn particular, 
defaultChina
default and other key players for achieving the necessary global action are unlikely to be impressed if the 
defaultUK
default builds a few extra wind farms or nuclear power plants.  They are likely to be impressed if the 
defaultUK
default takes a lead in deploying this novel 
defaultapproach to mitigating the risk of dangerous climate change
default.
default3.  The converse would also be likely.  The 
defaultUK
default 
defaulthas 
defaultpromoted CCS at the 2005 G8 Gleneagles Summit and subsequently as a 
defaultcritically important 
defaulttechnology for developing countries that rely on fossil fuels.  But the 
defaultUK
default itself, despite hav
defaulting (typically several)
default specific projects under d
defaultevelopment
default ever since then, has not yet committed to any significant investment.
default4.  CCS is a very effective way to stop fossil CO
default2
default entering the atmosphere
default.  It can, therefore, be expected to
default achieve rapid global emission reductions (see Figure 1) but 
defaultits deployment 
defaultrequires that money is spent solely for this purpose.  Demonstrating that the 
defaultUK
default is prepared to make this expenditure 
defaultis 
defaultitself probably at least as valuable in the global climate change mitigation process as 
defaultthe technical aspects of 
defaultdemonstrating some CCS technologies at full scale.
