defaultFigure 2 Tdefaulthreedefault times the amount defaultof fossil fuel reserves compared to allowable emissions seedefaultsdefault downward pressure on prices in defaultthe defaultIEA '450' Scenariodefault compared to increasing prices if current policies were continueddefault (IEA, World Energy Outlook 2012)default7.  In the longer term, if CO
default2
default concentrations in the atmosphere are not to rise, then net fossil
default fuel-generated
default emissions must fall close to zero.  Given the high value of unabated fossil fuel use for some transport applications and residual emissions from key activities such as food production then technologies to give net negative emissions to offset these could be very beneficial.  One such application is the use of biomass for power generation with CCS.  Another is direct capture of CO
default2
default from the air for secure storage.  While the latter might seem expensive at a possible cost of the order of several hundred pounds per tonne of CO
default2
default captured it is worth considering that carbon price of $200/tonne CO
default2
default would only add approximately $90 to the cost of a barrel of oil.  Also that a low-carbon technology that receives a subsidy of around £65/
defaultMWh
default (i.e. approx. $100/
defaultMWh
default) to displace natural gas generation with specific emissions of 0.5tCO
default2
default/
defaultMWh
default is already incurring an abatement cost of 
defaultaround 
default$200/tCO
default2
default.
default8.  The ability to achieve net negative global emissions would also theoretically be desirable if it became apparent that acceptable 
defaultgreenhouse gas
default levels in the atmosphere had been exceeded.  But atmospheric (and ocean) CO
default2
default accumulations are unlikely to be reduced fast enough by these means to reverse a rapid warming trend.  Costly negative emissions technology to reverse many years of unabated emissions would also impose a severe financial burden on future generations.
default&#xa0;
default9.  Assuming that a credible global approach to 
defaultgreenhouse gas
default emission reduction can be established, the 
defaultUK
default is expected to need to achieve rapid reductions in its own emissions to very low long term values (e.g. 80% reduction by 2050 and even lower after that
default based on analysis by the Committee on Climate Change
default).  This is likely to involve relatively rapid rollout of CCS in power generation and industry, based around clusters of CO
default2
default sources linked to a common CO
default2
default transport and storage infrastructure.  
defaultIn this context, a
defaultccelerating the development of CCS promises massive benefits – both in terms of savings on UK energy spend (up to £30bn a year by 2050
default has been estimated in Energy Technologies Institute studies
default) and 
defaultin terms of 
defaultenvironmental benefits because it is critical to achieving high levels of emissions reduction in the power and heat generation sectors and in energy-intensive manufacturing and process industries.  CCS offers a unique economic benefit by both creating new low-carbon jobs
default (based in part on existing 
defaultUK
default offshore engineering strengths)
default and protecting tens of thousands of jobs and 
defaultin 
default(currently) high carbon industries.  
default10.  In our previous work
default we have discussed the importance of completing two stages of full scale CCS deployment prior to wide scale rollout.  It can be expected that 'first of a kind' CCS projects in the UK and elsewhere will require some degree of defensive engineering in various elements of the CCS chain in order to accommodate regulatory uncertainty as well as technical novelty.  A second tranche of projects, designed against more normal commercial conditions and with the benefit of experience from previous design exercises and possibly operation, will therefore correspond more closely to 'reference plants', designs on which to base subsequent building in multiple numbers.
default11.  The key to ensuring that 2
defaultnd
default generation reference CCS projects can be undertaken in the 
defaultUK
default prior to a possible need for rollout in the 2020s is an early start on the first-of-a-kind projects.  This also has to be backed up by early transparency on how EMR will support further CCS projects and other measures to ensure continuity of effort in a nascent CCS industry.  Early action will also give more confidence for cluster development. Additionally, it is important to provide sources of CO
default2
default to allow verification of offshore storage capacity and may possibly also encourage enhanced oil recovery developments.  However urgent the subsequent need for CCS deployment to curb 
defaultUK
default emissions, it will still take a number of years to develop an understanding of CCS deployment under UK-specific conditions.  Failure to develop CCS in a timely manner now could lead to the need for the 
defaultUK
default (and other countries) to use sub-optimal approaches later through lack of the necessary experience, capacity and infrastructure.
default12.  Timely development for CCS technologies of particular importance for the 
defaultUK
default is likely to be heavily reliant on 
defaultUK
default efforts.  The Global CCS Institute's listing of 
defaultLarge-scale Integrated CCS Projects
default shows no large scale integrated CCS projects involving power generation are operating and only two are active (under construction, in North America) out of a total of 17 active projects. This compares to 8 active projects storing CO
default2
default that has to be separated anyway from natural gas production at CO
default2
default-rich fields (plus other projects using a range of other easily-accessed high-purity CO
default2
default sources) - see Figure 3.  More power CCS projects are planned, but many of these projects are not expected to progress to construction.  Recent experience and public domain information currently available on funding (and/or lack of funding) in Europe, where just a single power project (White Rose) applied for the second round of NER300 funding, suggests that only 3 projects (outlined in red 
defaultin
default Figure 4) are close to becoming active until further funds become available under UK EMR arrangements.  It therefore appears likely that the proposed 
defaultUK
default power CCS projects would make a significant contribution to the global development of CCS in this key sector. Clearly this also suggests that the 
defaultUK
default probably cannot rely on others to develop power sector technologies (particularly for capture from natural gas-fired power plants).  Offshore CO
default2
default storage (although not a category used in GCCSI lists) is another area that is central to future UK CCS needs but that is also not expected to be developed widely elsewhere in the near future.
